{"title_page": "Gerry Robinson", "text_new": "{{about||the football player|Jerry Robinson (American football)|the comics artist|Jerry Robinson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2009}}\n\n'''Sir Gerrard Jude \"Gerry\" Robinson''' (born 23 October 1948, [[Dunfanaghy]], [[County Donegal]], [[Ireland]]) is an Irish-born British business executive and television presenter. He is the former non-executive Chairman of [[Allied Domecq]] and the ex-Chairman/chief executive of [[Granada plc|Granada]].\n\n==Early life==\nThe ninth of 10 children born to Anthony and Elizabeth Robinson, an Irish father and a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother, Robinson moved with his family to England from [[County Donegal]] in his early teens. He briefly trained to become a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] priest at [[Castle Head, Grange-over-Sands|St. Mary's Seminary]] of the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]] at Castlehead, [[Grange-over-Sands]], [[Lancashire]]. He began a career in accounting in 1965 as a clerk with the [[Matchbox (brand)|Matchbox Toys]] company. While with the firm, he progressed through various accounting roles to become Chief Management Accountant in 1974. He also, during that time, qualified as an Associate Chartered Management Accountant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/gerry-robinson-sir/|title=Gerry Robinson, Sir - Personally Speaking Bureau|accessdate=4 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722072502/http://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/gerry-robinson-sir/|archive-date=22 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1974, he left Matchbox to work for [[Lex Vehicle Leasing]] as a management accountant. He then rose through the company before being appointed finance director. In 1980, he joined the UK franchise of [[Coca-Cola]], owned at that time by [[Grand Metropolitan]]. In 1983 he was appointed managing director of Grand Metropolitan's international services division. In 1987 he led the successful \u00a3163m management buyout of the loss-making contract services and catering division of [[Compass Group]], known as Compass Caterers. He joined [[Granada plc|Granada]] as CEO in 1991, and soon ousted Granada's chairman, [[David Plowright]] in 1992, which led [[John Cleese]] to call Robinson \"an upstart caterer \".<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1527549/David-Plowright.html|title=David Plowright obituary|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=30 August 2006|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nRobinson steered the company through various mergers, and hostile takeovers including [[London Weekend Television]] (1993) and [[Forte Group]] (1996). In 1999 Robinson was the subject of a biography, ''Lord of the Dance'', written by business journalist [[William Kay (journalist)|William Kay]], and published by Orion Business Books {{ISBN|0752810480}}. In 2005 he made an unsuccessful attempt to oust Doug Flynn as CEO of [[Rentokil Initial]] and install himself as Executive chairman for a 5% stake in the company, then valued at \u00a356M. {{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n==Television==\nRobinson's first foray into broadcasting was a revival of the [[BBC]]'s [[Troubleshooter (TV series)|''Troubleshooter'']] show, originally fronted by Sir [[John Harvey-Jones]] in the early 1990s. Titled ''I'll Show Them Who's Boss'' and co-produced by the [[Open University]], in 2004 he went into struggling businesses to try to turn them round by advice and mentoring.\n\nIn January 2007 following a similar format, he presented a three-part series, ''[[Can Gerry Robinson Fix the NHS?]]'' as he attempted to reduce waiting lists at [[Rotherham NHS Foundation Trust|Rotherham General Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open2.net/nhs/about_the_series.html|title=BBC/OU Open2.net, \"Can Gerry Robinson Fix The NHS?\"|publisher=Open2.net|date=|accessdate= 14 July 2009}}</ref> He returned a year later for a sequel, ''Can Gerry Robinson Fix the NHS? One Year On''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.open2.net/nhs/oneyearon/oneyearonsummary.html|title=BBC/OU Open2.net \u2013 Can Gerry Robinson Fix The NHS? One Year On|publisher=Open2.net|date=22 November 2007|accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> In December 2009, Robinson presented a programme in a similar format entitled ''Can Gerry Robinson Fix Dementia Care Homes?''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Can Gerry Robinson Fix Dementia Care Homes?|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00pf0s2|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 January 2014|author=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009 he presented a special edition of ''[[The Money Programme]]'' entitled ''Gerry Robinson's Car Crash'' investigating the history and future of the [[British motor industry]]. He regularly appears on British TV as a celebrity businessman.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1831101/bio IMDb bio]</ref> In July 2009 he started a TV series called ''Gerry's Big Decision'', in which he reviews struggling companies and decides whether it is worth investing his own money to save them.\nFrom 14 January \u2013 18 February 2011 he presented [[BBC2]] show ''Can't Take It with You'', which helps people to write their [[will (law)|will]]s.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00xk532]</ref>\n\n==Other affiliations==\nRobinson also served as chairman of the [[Arts Council England]] for six years from 1998, in which capacity he was one of the many victims of a spoof by British comedian [[Ali G]].<ref>[http://gerry-robinson-news.newslib.com Gerry Robinson official website]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRobinson has divorced and remarried and has four children. He lives in Raphoe,Co Donegal <ref>http://www.oakfieldpark.com/ Oakfield Park</ref> ; he established a botanical garden with a narrow gauge railway \u2013 the Difflin Lake Railway \u2013 which is open to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2007/10/07/story27146.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214073506/http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2007/10/07/story27146.asp |archivedate=14 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nAlthough originally a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] supporter, he supported [[Tony Blair]] and starred in a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[party political broadcast|election broadcast]], saying that ''\"... frankly, there's only one party that can represent Britain best, getting business right, and that's New Labour\"''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardianlies.com/Granada%20TV/page3.html|title=Granada TV Part Two: Comrades at the Top|publisher=GuardianLies.com|accessdate=14 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911030207/http://www.guardianlies.com/Granada%20TV/page3.html|archivedate=11 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2008, Robinson was one of four Labour donors who expressed their concerns with [[Gordon Brown]]'s leadership and stated he would not be contributing any more money to the Labour Party until there was a change of leader. He had donated some \u00a370,000 to the party between 2001 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7479840.stm|title=Labour donor says Brown must go|work=BBC News|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHe was knighted in the [[2004 New Year Honours]] List.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* 1999: Lord of the Dance, the story of Sir Gerry Robinson, by William Kay. Orion. {{ISBN|0-7528-1048-0}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071025082155/http://news.independent.co.uk/business/analysis_and_features/article2470138.ece Interview in ''The Independent'']\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7479840.stm \"Labour donor says Brown must go\", BBC News 29 June 2008]\n* Gerry Robinson on his admiration for Samuel Beckett, BBC Radio 4 Great Lives \u2013 listen online: http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wqbjq\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Alexander Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie|Lord Gowrie]]|title=[[Arts Council England|Chair of Arts Council England]]\n|years=1998\u20132004|after=[[Christopher Frayling]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Gerry}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Irish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:ITV people]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People from Dunfanaghy]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) donors]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) donors]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the football player|Jerry Robinson (American football)|the comics artist|Jerry Robinson}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More footnotes|date=October 2009}}\n\n'''Sir Gerrard Jude \"Gerry\" Robinson''' (born 23 October 1948, [[Dunfanaghy]], [[County Donegal]], [[Ireland]]) is an Irish-born British business executive and television presenter. He is the former non-executive Chairman of [[Allied Domecq]] and the ex-Chairman/chief executive of [[Granada plc|Granada]].\n\n==Early life==\nThe ninth of 10 children born to Anthony and Elizabeth Robinson, an Irish father and a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mother, Robinson moved with his family to England from [[County Donegal]] in his early teens. He briefly trained to become a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] priest at [[Castle Head, Grange-over-Sands|St. Mary's Seminary]] of the [[Holy Ghost Fathers]] at Castlehead, [[Grange-over-Sands]], [[Lancashire]]. He began a career in accounting in 1965 as a clerk with the [[Matchbox (brand)|Matchbox Toys]] company. While with the firm, he progressed through various accounting roles to become Chief Management Accountant in 1974. He also, during that time, qualified as an Associate Chartered Management Accountant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/gerry-robinson-sir/|title=Gerry Robinson, Sir - Personally Speaking Bureau|accessdate=4 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722072502/http://www.personallyspeakingbureau.com/speaker/gerry-robinson-sir/|archive-date=22 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1974, he left Matchbox to work for [[Lex Vehicle Leasing]] as a management accountant. He then rose through the company before being appointed finance director. In 1980, he joined the UK franchise of [[Coca-Cola]], owned at that time by [[Grand Metropolitan]]. In 1983 he was appointed managing director of Grand Metropolitan's international services division. In 1987 he led the successful \u00a3163m management buyout of the loss-making contract services and catering division of [[Compass Group]], known as Compass Caterers. He joined [[Granada plc|Granada]] as CEO in 1991, and soon ousted Granada's chairman, [[David Plowright]] in 1992, which led [[John Cleese]] to call Robinson \"an upstart caterer \".<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1527549/David-Plowright.html|title=David Plowright obituary|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=30 August 2006|accessdate=17 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nRobinson steered the company through various mergers, and hostile takeovers including [[London Weekend Television]] (1993) and [[Forte Group]] (1996). In 1999 Robinson was the subject of a biography, ''Lord of the Dance'', written by business journalist [[William Kay (journalist)|William Kay]], and published by Orion Business Books {{ISBN|0752810480}}. In 2005 he made an unsuccessful attempt to oust Doug Flynn as CEO of [[Rentokil Initial]] and install himself as Executive chairman for a 5% stake in the company, then valued at \u00a356M. {{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\n==Television==\nRobinson's first foray into broadcasting was a revival of the [[BBC]]'s [[T