p://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00xk532]</ref>\n\n==Other affiliations==\nRobinson also served as chairman of the [[Arts Council England]] for six years from 1998, in which capacity he was one of the many victims of a spoof by British comedian [[Ali G]].<ref>[http://gerry-robinson-news.newslib.com Gerry Robinson official website]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRobinson has divorced and remarried and has four children. He lives in Raphoe,Co Donegal <ref>http://www.oakfieldpark.com/ Oakfield Park</ref> ; he established a botanical garden with a narrow gauge railway \u2013 the Difflin Lake Railway \u2013 which is open to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2007/10/07/story27146.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214073506/http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2007/10/07/story27146.asp |archivedate=14 December 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nAlthough originally a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] supporter, he supported [[Tony Blair]] and starred in a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[party political broadcast|election broadcast]], saying that ''\"... frankly, there's only one party that can represent Britain best, getting business right, and that's New Labour\"''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardianlies.com/Granada%20TV/page3.html|title=Granada TV Part Two: Comrades at the Top|publisher=GuardianLies.com|accessdate=14 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090911030207/http://www.guardianlies.com/Granada%20TV/page3.html|archivedate=11 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2008, Robinson was one of four Labour donors who expressed their concerns with [[Gordon Brown]]'s leadership and stated he would not be contributing any more money to the Labour Party until there was a change of leader. He had donated some \u00a370,000 to the party between 2001 and 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7479840.stm|title=Labour donor says Brown must go|work=BBC News|date=29 June 2008|accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHe was knighted in the [[2004 New Year Honours]] List.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* 1999: Lord of the Dance, the story of Sir Gerry Robinson, by William Kay. Orion. {{ISBN|0-7528-1048-0}}.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071025082155/http://news.independent.co.uk/business/analysis_and_features/article2470138.ece Interview in ''The Independent'']\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7479840.stm \"Labour donor says Brown must go\", BBC News 29 June 2008]\n* Gerry Robinson on his admiration for Samuel Beckett, BBC Radio 4 Great Lives \u2013 listen online: http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00wqbjq\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Alexander Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie|Lord Gowrie]]|title=[[Arts Council England|Chair of Arts Council England]]\n|years=1998\u20132004|after=[[Christopher Frayling]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Gerry}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Irish businesspeople]]\n[[Category:ITV people]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People from Dunfanaghy]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "HonkyDory64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Labour Party donor)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerry_Robinson"}
